                      <span>2</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2004-05-27</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>The book gives a complete history of open source development starting from the earlier days of RMS and Linus. The strong point of the book is that the depth of coverage on open source history is unmatchable.  My most favourite chapters are the ones that describe the early development of Linux and the history of Perl. <p>Reading the book gives the impression that author's bias against the RMS-style free-software. Also the author gives enough hints of his dislike for Microsoft's style of proprietary software. And towards the end, as the author starts explaining linux' entry into the corporate place, the book tends to be a bit dragging.<p>Overall, a must read for any open source enthusiast.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">For My Hubby</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
